Common questions

Things people ask before they switch.

Most EV objections turn out to be less of a problem than people expect.

What if I don't have a driveway?
+
More than a million UK EV drivers charge without home charging. Lamp-post chargers, workplace charging, and rapid chargers at supermarkets cover most commutes. PHEVs are a great option if you do longer journeys — electric for daily runs, petrol for everything else.
Are used EVs reliable? What about the battery?
+
Modern EV batteries are covered by manufacturer warranty for 8 years or 100,000 miles. Degradation is typically less than 10% over 8 years. carwow shows certified battery health data on every used EV listing.
What is BiK tax and how much could I save?
+
Benefit-in-Kind (BiK) is the tax paid on a company car. For diesel, it's typically 35–37% of list value. For an EV, BiK is just 2% until 2026. On a £40,000 company car, the difference is over £3,000 a year in take-home pay.
Do I need to worry about range?
+
For most UK drivers, 200+ miles real-world range covers a full working week. Range anxiety typically fades within the first month. For regular long trips, a PHEV is the smarter starting point — no compromises at all.
Is carwow free to use?
+
Completely free for drivers — always has been. Dealers pay to be on the platform, which is also why they offer genuinely competitive prices. No hidden fees, no subscription, no obligation to buy anything.
What's the difference between BEV, PHEV and mild hybrid?
+
BEV (Battery Electric) runs entirely on electricity — zero tailpipe emissions. PHEV (Plug-in Hybrid) has a chargeable battery plus petrol for longer journeys. MHEV (Mild Hybrid) assists a petrol engine but can't run on electricity alone. PHEVs are the most popular first step.
